, by the 1860s, despite his determined resistance, he was an oppressed subject of harsh British colonial rule. In this innovative, richly researched, and splendidly written biography, Roger S. Levine reclaims Tzatzoe's lost story and analyzes his contributions to, and experiences with, the turbulent colonial world to argue for the crucial role of Africans as agents of cultural and intellectual change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChristian biographyzSouth Africa. 0aMissionarieszSouth AfricavBiography. 0aSocial changezSouth AfricaxHistoryy19th century. 0aXhosa (African people)xKings and rulersvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831105379940 cprintz978030012521440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030016859440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300168594423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300168594/original  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY